In order to modify the error values, create a vector named ‘search_values’. Using ‘%in%’ allows referencing zipcode data from ‘L$zipcode’ and returns a binary value. As this is a binary function, it is possible to create a new data frame to display the searched data. The empty operator, such as ‘[matching_zipcodes, ]’, necessitates quoting every searched row based on the zip codes.

I-2. Visit frequency per arrondissement and month.

I-2.a. Create a data frame named ‘Visit’ using the right_join function to count the number of listing IDs based on the zip code and month.

Visit <- right_join(select(L, id, zipcode), R, by = c("id" = "listing_id"))

Visit$date <- as.Date(Visit$date)
Visit <- Visit %>%
  mutate(month = month(date))

Visit$zipcode <- as.numeric(as.character(Visit$zipcode))
Paris <- Visit %>%
  filter(zipcode >= 75001 & zipcode <= 75020)
Paris$zipcode <- as.numeric(as.character(Paris$zipcode))

I-3.d. Trend of price per arrondissement

Price.Paris.grouped = group_by(Price.Paris, zipcode)
  Summ_price = summarise(Price.Paris.grouped, 
                price_mean = mean(price, na.rm = TRUE),
                price_sd = sd(price, na.rm = TRUE))
  Summ_price
Q1 <- quantile(Summ_price$price_mean, 0.25)
Q3 <- quantile(Summ_price$price_mean, 0.75)
IQR <- Q3 - Q1

lower_bound <- Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound <- Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
outliers <- Summ_price$price_mean[Summ_price$price_mean < lower_bound | Summ_price$price_mean > upper_bound]

Price_mean_noOutliers <- Summ_price[!Summ_price$price_mean %in% outliers, ]

boxplot(Price_mean_noOutliers$price_mean,         
main = "Boxplot of Price (without outliers)",        
ylab = "price_mean")

Present a boxplot to visualize the mean price, cleally showing that prices are genrally formed around 30-100 dollors.

ggplot(data = Price_mean_noOutliers) +
  theme_light() +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = factor(zipcode), y = price_mean))

According to the summury table, the everage price is 103.26. comparing this number, the first area of Paris has the most highest everage whereas 19th,20th areas have less than 50, indicating the most significant decline.

Paris’s 75005th arrondissement may have higher property values or rental prices, whereas the area around zipcode 75020 has relatively lower values.

The number of Entire home/apt is the highest, in terms of price. The number of bedrooms has an impact on increasing the rental price. Secondly, the private room has a higher price structure than the shared room.

Comparing the number of bedrooms, there are more of them. Concerning the Entire home/apt, it seems to be less expensive. On the other hand, in the Shared room, the price increases. Merely, it is noted that in the Private room, there is also an increase in the average rental price.

II-1.e. Number of Accommodates and Room type

avg_price_by_accommodates <- Features %>%
  group_by(accommodates, room_type) %>%
  summarise(mean_price = mean(price, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop')

ggplot(avg_price_by_accommodates, aes(x = accommodates, y = mean_price, fill = room_type)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge()) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Average Price by Number of Accommodates for Each Room Type",
       x = "Number of Accommodates",
       y = "Average Price ($)") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2")

Prices less than the average tend to increase with the number of accommodations, whereas prices for more than 12 accommodations decline. Generally, it seems that around 7-8 accommodations approach the average rental price.

II-1.f. Bed type and Room type

avg_price_by_bedtype_and_room <- Features %>%

ggplot(avg_price_by_bedtype_and_room, aes(x = bed_type, y = mean_price, fill = room_type)) +

       y = "Average Price ($)") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set3") +
  theme(legend.title = element_blank(), legend.position = "top")

In the entire home/apt, the real bed is the most expensive. On the other hand, the airbed seems to be the least popular. This movement in price may reflect the quality of sleep.

III-1.c. Understand the proportion of rented apartment numbers..

count1 <- exam_Hosts %>%
  filter(frequency < 2) %>%
  count()

count2 <- exam_Hosts %>%
  filter(frequency > 1 & frequency < 51) %>%
  count()

count3 <- exam_Hosts %>%
  filter(frequency > 50) %>%
  count()

count.combined <- rbind(count1, count2, count3)

rownames(count.combined) <- c("Nb APT < 2", "1 < Nb APT < 51", "Nb APT > 50")

count.combined$Percentage <- count.combined$n / sum(count.combined$n) * 100

print(count.combined)
##                     n  Percentage
## Nb APT < 2      40209 92.94514690
## 1 < Nb APT < 51  3037  7.02017984
## Nb APT > 50        15  0.03467326
pie_labels <- paste0(rownames(count.combined), ": ", round(count.combined$Percentage, 2), "%")

pie(count.combined$Percentage,
    labels = pie_labels,
    col = c('lightblue', 'pink', 'lightgreen'),
    main = "Percentage Distribution")

legend("topright",
       legend = rownames(count.combined),
       fill = c('lightblue', 'pink', 'lightgreen'))

After the dataset, the total number of existing Airbnb quarters is 52,725, with apartments occupied at 76%. Considering only apartments, there are 93% of hosts renting only one apartment and only around 7% of hosts renting more than one apartment. It’s possible for an organization or professional to manage the apartments.
